[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1400},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F01\u002F24\u002Fjavascript-core-48-where-is-the-prototype\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F01\u002F24\u002Fjavascript-core-48-where-is-the-prototype\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F01\u002F24\u002Fjavascript-core-48-where-is-the-prototype\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F01\u002F24\u002Fjavascript-core-48-where-is-the-prototype\u002F":1376,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F01\u002F24\u002Fjavascript-core-48-where-is-the-prototype\u002F":1385},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20210124\u002F2151565856\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1360,"date":1361,"description":1362,"extension":1363,"lang":1364,"meta":1365,"navigation":349,"path":1366,"readingMinutes":481,"seo":1367,"standalone":1368,"stem":1369,"tags":1370,"tldr":1373,"updated":1361,"url":1374,"__hash__":1375},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjavascript-core-48-where-is-the-prototype.md","JavaScript Core Concepts (48) — Inheritance & Prototype Chain: Where Does the Prototype Live?","1001005716",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1354},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,31,34,133,136,139,200,203,206,212,215,221,224,228,231,244,247,292,303,310,388,391,536,539,701,704,961,973,993,996,1093,1099,1219,1232,1243,1336,1340,1350],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"Starting with this chapter, we're finally going to get into prototypes for real.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"prototypes","Prototypes",[17,25,26],{},[27,28],"img",{"alt":29,"src":30},"Prototype","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202021-01-24%2016.09.29.png",[17,32,33],{},"Let's start with an example. Say we define a dog object — it'd look something like this:",[35,36,41],"pre",{"className":37,"code":38,"language":39,"meta":40,"style":40},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","var bibi = {\n  color: 'brown',\n  size: 'small',\n  bark: function() {\n    console.log('woof');\n  }\n};\n","js","",[42,43,44,63,76,87,103,121,127],"code",{"__ignoreMap":40},[45,46,49,53,57,60],"span",{"class":47,"line":48},"line",1,[45,50,52],{"class":51},"sWyjQ","var",[45,54,56],{"class":55},"sMAXC"," bibi ",[45,58,59],{"class":51},"=",[45,61,62],{"class":55}," {\n",[45,64,66,69,73],{"class":47,"line":65},2,[45,67,68],{"class":55},"  color: ",[45,70,72],{"class":71},"sTRMh","'brown'",[45,74,75],{"class":55},",\n",[45,77,79,82,85],{"class":47,"line":78},3,[45,80,81],{"class":55},"  size: ",[45,83,84],{"class":71},"'small'",[45,86,75],{"class":55},[45,88,90,94,97,100],{"class":47,"line":89},4,[45,91,93],{"class":92},"sj_SG","  bark",[45,95,96],{"class":55},": ",[45,98,99],{"class":51},"function",[45,101,102],{"class":55},"() {\n",[45,104,106,109,112,115,118],{"class":47,"line":105},5,[45,107,108],{"class":55},"    console.",[45,110,111],{"class":92},"log",[45,113,114],{"class":55},"(",[45,116,117],{"class":71},"'woof'",[45,119,120],{"class":55},");\n",[45,122,124],{"class":47,"line":123},6,[45,125,126],{"class":55},"  }\n",[45,128,130],{"class":47,"line":129},7,[45,131,132],{"class":55},"};\n",[17,134,135],{},"When we want to grab any property, we use the dot operator (or square brackets) to read it. This is your everyday JavaScript object.",[17,137,138],{},"The thing I really want to stress here is the same one as always — \"JavaScript is made up of objects.\" And the prototype concept is basically the same idea. We just take the properties every dog has and turn them into a prototype. And even at the prototype level, you still can't escape objects:",[35,140,142],{"className":37,"code":141,"language":39,"meta":40,"style":40},"var aDog = {\n  color: theDogsColor,\n  size: theDogsSize,\n  bark: function() {\n    console.log('woof'); \u002F\u002F something every dog does\n  }\n};\n",[42,143,144,155,160,165,175,192,196],{"__ignoreMap":40},[45,145,146,148,151,153],{"class":47,"line":48},[45,147,52],{"class":51},[45,149,150],{"class":55}," aDog ",[45,152,59],{"class":51},[45,154,62],{"class":55},[45,156,157],{"class":47,"line":65},[45,158,159],{"class":55},"  color: theDogsColor,\n",[45,161,162],{"class":47,"line":78},[45,163,164],{"class":55},"  size: theDogsSize,\n",[45,166,167,169,171,173],{"class":47,"line":89},[45,168,93],{"class":92},[45,170,96],{"class":55},[45,172,99],{"class":51},[45,174,102],{"class":55},[45,176,177,179,181,183,185,188],{"class":47,"line":105},[45,178,108],{"class":55},[45,180,111],{"class":92},[45,182,114],{"class":55},[45,184,117],{"class":71},[45,186,187],{"class":55},"); ",[45,189,191],{"class":190},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F something every dog does\n",[45,193,194],{"class":47,"line":123},[45,195,126],{"class":55},[45,197,198],{"class":47,"line":129},[45,199,132],{"class":55},[17,201,202],{},"So when a dog needs to create an instance (basically, get brought to life), it gets built based on the dog prototype. Which means it's really two objects, with one inheriting from the other.",[17,204,205],{},"And a prototype itself usually inherits from another prototype, and that other prototype has its own properties and methods too. So the prototype keeps looking upward, level by level — and that chain of looking up is what we call the prototype chain.",[17,207,208],{},[27,209],{"alt":210,"src":211},"Prototype chain","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202021-01-24%2016.24.19.png",[17,213,214],{},"If the method you call isn't on the instance itself, the instance walks up through the prototype chain, and it keeps going up and up until it either finds the method or hits the top. The concept is really similar to the scope chain.",[17,216,217],{},[27,218],{"alt":219,"src":220},"Looking up the chain","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202021-01-24%2016.27.14.png",[17,222,223],{},"One extra note here: if you have two instances both built from the same prototype, then those instances will look up the same prototype.",[12,225,227],{"id":226},"characteristics-of-prototypes","Characteristics of Prototypes",[17,229,230],{},"So here's a quick rundown of what prototypes basically are:",[232,233,234,238,241],"ul",{},[235,236,237],"li",{},"They have all the characteristics of objects",[235,239,240],{},"They have the look-upward behavior",[235,242,243],{},"Prototypes can share methods and properties",[17,245,246],{},"The clearest way to get this is to jump straight into a real example:",[35,248,250],{"className":37,"code":249,"language":39,"meta":40,"style":40},"var arr = [1, 2, 3];\nconsole.log(arr);\n",[42,251,252,282],{"__ignoreMap":40},[45,253,254,256,259,261,264,268,271,274,276,279],{"class":47,"line":48},[45,255,52],{"class":51},[45,257,258],{"class":55}," arr ",[45,260,59],{"class":51},[45,262,263],{"class":55}," [",[45,265,267],{"class":266},"sCcAr","1",[45,269,270],{"class":55},", ",[45,272,273],{"class":266},"2",[45,275,270],{"class":55},[45,277,278],{"class":266},"3",[45,280,281],{"class":55},"];\n",[45,283,284,287,289],{"class":47,"line":65},[45,285,286],{"class":55},"console.",[45,288,111],{"class":92},[45,290,291],{"class":55},"(arr);\n",[17,293,294,295,298,299,302],{},"So what's the instance here? ",[42,296,297],{},"arr"," is the instance. And where's the prototype? If you paste this code into the console and expand the output, you'll find a ",[42,300,301],{},"__proto__"," inside — that's the Array prototype, and it holds a ton of array methods. I won't screenshot it here; if you're curious, just run it yourself and poke around.",[17,304,305,306,309],{},"Back to prototypes — we said an instance can use the prototype's own properties and methods, which is why we can call common methods like ",[42,307,308],{},"arr.forEach",":",[35,311,313],{"className":37,"code":312,"language":39,"meta":40,"style":40},"var arr = [1, 2, 3];\nconsole.log(arr);\n\narr.forEach(function (item) {\n  console.log(item);\n})\n",[42,314,315,337,345,351,373,383],{"__ignoreMap":40},[45,316,317,319,321,323,325,327,329,331,333,335],{"class":47,"line":48},[45,318,52],{"class":51},[45,320,258],{"class":55},[45,322,59],{"class":51},[45,324,263],{"class":55},[45,326,267],{"class":266},[45,328,270],{"class":55},[45,330,273],{"class":266},[45,332,270],{"class":55},[45,334,278],{"class":266},[45,336,281],{"class":55},[45,338,339,341,343],{"class":47,"line":65},[45,340,286],{"class":55},[45,342,111],{"class":92},[45,344,291],{"class":55},[45,346,347],{"class":47,"line":78},[45,348,350],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":349},true,"\n",[45,352,353,356,359,361,363,366,370],{"class":47,"line":89},[45,354,355],{"class":55},"arr.",[45,357,358],{"class":92},"forEach",[45,360,114],{"class":55},[45,362,99],{"class":51},[45,364,365],{"class":55}," (",[45,367,369],{"class":368},"s_sBn","item",[45,371,372],{"class":55},") {\n",[45,374,375,378,380],{"class":47,"line":105},[45,376,377],{"class":55},"  console.",[45,379,111],{"class":92},[45,381,382],{"class":55},"(item);\n",[45,384,385],{"class":47,"line":123},[45,386,387],{"class":55},"})\n",[17,389,390],{},"Next we can verify another thing — that \"a prototype's methods and properties are shared.\" So if we declare another array, it can use the exact same methods:",[35,392,394],{"className":37,"code":393,"language":39,"meta":40,"style":40},"var arr = [1, 2, 3];\nconsole.log(arr);\n\narr.forEach(function (item) {\n  console.log(item);\n})\n\nvar arr2 = [4, 5, 6];\nconsole.log(arr2);\n\narr2.forEach(function (item) {\n  console.log(item);\n})\n",[42,395,396,418,426,430,446,454,458,462,489,499,504,522,531],{"__ignoreMap":40},[45,397,398,400,402,404,406,408,410,412,414,416],{"class":47,"line":48},[45,399,52],{"class":51},[45,401,258],{"class":55},[45,403,59],{"class":51},[45,405,263],{"class":55},[45,407,267],{"class":266},[45,409,270],{"class":55},[45,411,273],{"class":266},[45,413,270],{"class":55},[45,415,278],{"class":266},[45,417,281],{"class":55},[45,419,420,422,424],{"class":47,"line":65},[45,421,286],{"class":55},[45,423,111],{"class":92},[45,425,291],{"class":55},[45,427,428],{"class":47,"line":78},[45,429,350],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":349},[45,431,432,434,436,438,440,442,444],{"class":47,"line":89},[45,433,355],{"class":55},[45,435,358],{"class":92},[45,437,114],{"class":55},[45,439,99],{"class":51},[45,441,365],{"class":55},[45,443,369],{"class":368},[45,445,372],{"class":55},[45,447,448,450,452],{"class":47,"line":105},[45,449,377],{"class":55},[45,451,111],{"class":92},[45,453,382],{"class":55},[45,455,456],{"class":47,"line":123},[45,457,387],{"class":55},[45,459,460],{"class":47,"line":129},[45,461,350],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":349},[45,463,465,467,470,472,474,477,479,482,484,487],{"class":47,"line":464},8,[45,466,52],{"class":51},[45,468,469],{"class":55}," arr2 ",[45,471,59],{"class":51},[45,473,263],{"class":55},[45,475,476],{"class":266},"4",[45,478,270],{"class":55},[45,480,481],{"class":266},"5",[45,483,270],{"class":55},[45,485,486],{"class":266},"6",[45,488,281],{"class":55},[45,490,492,494,496],{"class":47,"line":491},9,[45,493,286],{"class":55},[45,495,111],{"class":92},[45,497,498],{"class":55},"(arr2);\n",[45,500,502],{"class":47,"line":501},10,[45,503,350],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":349},[45,505,507,510,512,514,516,518,520],{"class":47,"line":506},11,[45,508,509],{"class":55},"arr2.",[45,511,358],{"class":92},[45,513,114],{"class":55},[45,515,99],{"class":51},[45,517,365],{"class":55},[45,519,369],{"class":368},[45,521,372],{"class":55},[45,523,525,527,529],{"class":47,"line":524},12,[45,526,377],{"class":55},[45,528,111],{"class":92},[45,530,382],{"class":55},[45,532,534],{"class":47,"line":533},13,[45,535,387],{"class":55},[17,537,538],{},"But just looking at the above, you can't rea